"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061224","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-02-22","<p>Vaccines are an important tool for the prevention of infection, as highlighted in the United Kingdom Government’s 20-year vision on antimicrobial resistance, which is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-20-year-vision-for-antimicrobial-resistance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-20-year-vision-for-antimicrobial-resistance</a></p><p>Uptake and assessment of coverage of new vaccines to help prevent antimicrobial resistance will be dependent on how successful research programmes for the development of new products in this area progress. This remains under constant review.</p><p> </p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-02-22T11:47:32.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061224/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061224/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-14","Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department plans to review its targets for coverage and uptake of vaccines that help prevent antimicrobial resistance as a result of the Government’s new Antimicrobial Resistance Strategy, published on 24 January 2019.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","221732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061225","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-02-22","<p>The Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation (JCVI) is aware that vaccination has an important role in controlling antimicrobial resistance but considers that current models are not sufficiently developed to fully estimate and quantify the potential impact of vaccines on the burden of antimicrobial resistance. Many of the potential benefits of vaccination in relation to antimicrobial resistance (AMR) cannot therefore be easily included in estimates of cost-effectiveness.</p><p>The JCVI has suggested that better tools need to be developed to estimate and quantify the potential impact of vaccines in reducing the long-term burden of AMR. This could then inform cost-effectiveness analyses. The National Institute of Health Research, Health Protection Research Unit, based at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, is currently working on the development of such models.</p><p>As most resistant infections are healthcare associated, the new JCVI Healthcare Associated Infections Working Group, set up to review and provide preliminary advice to JCVI on the potential use of appropriate vaccines in the United Kingdom, will help to address this issue.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-02-22T08:22:45.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061225/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061225/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-14","Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what plans the Government has to work with the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation to establish a value assessment measure of antimicrobial resistance in the consideration of existing and new immunisation programmes.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","221733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061226","Home Office","false","2019-02-19","<p>Home Office published statistics on visitor entry clearance visas start from 2005.</p><p>Information on visitor entry clearance visa applications and outcomes (grants, refusals, withdrawn and lapsed cases) is published on a quarterly basis as part of the Home Office publication scheme, in the Home Office’s ‘Immigration Statistics’, Visas data tables volume 1, table vi_01_q.</p><p>The latest edition can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-year-ending-september-2018/list-of-tables#visas" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-year-ending-september-2018/list-of-tables#visas</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-02-19T14:34:17.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061226/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061226/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-02-14","Visas: Overseas Visitors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of visit visa applications have been refused in each year since 2000.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","221834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061227","Department of Health and Social Care","true","2019-02-19","<p>The proportion of general practitioner (GP) appointments by date and time between booking date and appointment date in Oxford Clinical Commissioning Group for the months November 2017 to December 2018 is presented in the attached table. The data on GP appointments are from a new data collection and are still experimental i.e. the data and collection method are still being refined and improved. NHS Digital’s data on ‘time from booking to appointment’ does not take into consideration that many patients will be appropriately booking ahead as part of the continuity of care they receive for long-term conditions. Other factors that drive the time from a booking to an appointment include appointment availability at the practice, patient availability, the urgency of the appointment and GP advice.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-02-19T17:24:06.47Z","2019-02-21T10:24:53.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061227/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061227/answer","221835 formatted table.docx","221835 formatted table.docx","GP appointments Oxford CCG","GP appointments Oxford CCG","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061227/answer","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061227/answer/previousversion/103151","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061227/answer/previousversion/103151","PQ221587 attached tables.docx","PQ221835 attached table","17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-14","General Practitioners: Oxford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment he has made of trends in the level of GP appointment waiting times in Oxford.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","221835"
