"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061230","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-02-22","<p>The Department has extensive arrangements in place to ensure that people can access affordable prescriptions for which someone with asthma may qualify. A broad range of prescription charge exemptions are in place, and, to support those with greatest need who do not qualify for an exemption, prescription prepayment certificates are available. A holder of a 12-month certificate can get all the prescriptions they need for just £2 per week. There are no current plans to amend the list of medical conditions that provides exemption from prescription charges.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-02-22T08:14:03.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061230/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1061230/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-14","Asthma: Prescriptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he has put in place plans to support asthma sufferers with the cost of their prescriptions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","221838"
